        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_0_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Those are fair criticisms -- I think folks are naturally skeptical of anything that sounds too "markety," so I hope we don't come across as that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_0_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We're actually just a bunch of guys working out of home offices.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_0_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A few disconnected thoughts: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_0_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is really just a first stab at a survey.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_0_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I asked a bunch of fellow indies what they wanted to poll for, and boiled that down to what you guys see here.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_0_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>With feedback, I figure we can improve next time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_0_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Content is actually something I feel that the devs I talk to are really good at!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_0_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Forget the studios that churn out cheap crap -- I think a culture is emerging where indies want to one-up each other on creativity and polish.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_0_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Indie" to me means a small studio that can use the word "fucktardbutthead" in a game's title if they want, or create a game mechanic about sorting dogs by smell without worrying about getting fired.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_0_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I think it's a good thing, because each of these small games lives or dies based on what gamers actually like to play.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_1_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I appreciate your taking the time to write that out.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_1_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's some of the first feedback we've received.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_1_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You raise a point in particular with free/donationware games, which I hadn't even considered!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_2_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Re: part-time job: How on Earth did I miss that?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_2_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thanks for the catch and for the feedback. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_3_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I didn't mean for it to, but now I suppose the game will have to have it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_3_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One of our college interns did that building in Maya -- he's also a big-time Reddit user.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_3_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Coincidence or the unconscious mind at work?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_3_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You be the judge!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_4_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They created Weird Worlds: Return to Infinite Space, and have won about a bazillion IGF awards.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_4_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We haven't won any.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_5_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's not just about marketing.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_5_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I use the term "soft cheeses" too.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_6_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thank you!!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_7_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm glad I didn't tell CollectiveNoun "No, I can't give you a copy of the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_7_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I have a stick up my butt." :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_8_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We wrote AaaaaAAaaaAAAaaAAAAaAAAAA!!!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_8_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>using the 3DGS engine, in a combination of C++ and C-Script.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_8_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But Unity 3D is also really powerful and popular, so you might look at that as a good starting point.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_8_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There's even a free version!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_9_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Had I known about this, I'd have posted it to the blog.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_9_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Awesome. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_10_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Well, the iOS version of AaaaaAAaaaAAAaaAAAAaAAAAA!!!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_10_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>is going to be called AaaaaAAaaaAAAaaAAAAaAAAAA!!! (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_10_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Force = Mass x Acceleration), and our 2012 title is going to be called Drunken Robot Pornography.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_10_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm not sure if those are good or not; I'm afraid to ask. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_11_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Well, this is it, ladies and gents.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_11_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Our iOS launch.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_11_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Here's a trailer: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aSSVX7j7efY amp;feature=g-upl amp;context=G236e51eAUAAAAAAAAAA</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_12_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ninety-nine.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_13_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yeah, here's a map of where we are: http://marctenbosch.com/megabooth/map.html</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_14_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We're like the anti-rappers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_15_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt; ...that involves mexican wrestlers falling great distances... As you know, ECB, my studio created a game called MmmmmMMmmmMMMmmMMMMmMMMMM!!!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_15_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>which is about Mexican wrestlers falling, so yes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_15_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But what would the game look like?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_16_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I played Journey for 15 minutes in front of a group of non-gamers right after we ate dinner, so there was a confluence of "Oooh!"</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_16_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>combined with "Man, this is slow."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_16_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I do want to pick it up at some point and just play it for a weekend.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_17_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In Dejobaan's case, we basically take all the wonderful ideas we have (and everyone who plays games has 'em), pick the most promising ones, and prototype 'em.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_17_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We then triage -- things that look like they may become games, we iterate on.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_17_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A lot of neat things don't make it: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sKZMnm6hehE</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_18_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We tend to target hardcore gamers, but I think we're trying to open that up.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_18_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What hit me last year, was when we did the Potato ARG, if you're familiar with it -- I thought folks wanted really tough, punishing gameplay, but I think we should have gone for just plain old fun.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_18_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Lesson learned.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_18_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What kinds of games do you play?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_19_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yes; from what I understand, they're focused more on AAA studios, so the end result of 9-18 months' hard work is the sound of crickets. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_19_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Do you have any fave indie games on those platforms?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_20_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Did you get a chance to play it alone, afterwards?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_21_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I think Fooood is flattering us.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_21_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But how about: the times when we're not awesome, we go out of business, and have to eat ramen noodles, so we try to make our games as good as we can. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_22_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I love this question.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_22_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's tough, because it depends (in part) on what's around you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_22_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Where are you, geographically?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_23_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In general, I think that all of us are always looking for new contributors, even if we don't know it. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_23_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As simple as it sounds, some of the best folks I've worked with are those whom I've just met many times in Boston-area events (for example) -- if I like their work, and they're intelligent and cool, it's almost a no-brainer, once I need a new artist or coder or such.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_23_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt; And also what kind of stuff do you look for if you are?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_23_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Depends on the project, but for an artist, I always want to see someone who can draw a human figure well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_24_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Aw, we're right next to the ocean.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_24_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Salt's free.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_24_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As is mercury poisoning.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_24_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>@narrativedesigner: We are giving away free mercury at the booth, if you like(?)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_25_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The bastids! -</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_25_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>gt; http://marctenbosch.com/megabooth/map.html</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_26_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This isn't from last year, but have you played Captain Forever?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_26_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>http://www.captainforever.com/captainforever.php Wikipedia description: "In each game in the series, with the exception of Captain Impostor, the player pilots a ship with the ability to be expanded by attaching 'modules' (such as lasers or boosters) gained from defeated enemies to a command module, represented by a box containing a broken heart.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_26_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The goal in the game is to keep your ship alive for as long as possible.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_26_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As the game progresses, stronger enemy ships (labeled according to letters from the NATO phonetic alphabet) arrive.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_26_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Destroying stronger ships increases the Law (levels within the game), until Protectors (Peacekeepers in the original game) arrive to attack.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_26_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The game effectively ends after the first Protector is destroyed (replacing the command module's broken heart with a complete one) but the player may continue accumulating parts indefinitely.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_26_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If the player's ship is destroyed, it explodes, destroying all ships in the immediate area and clearing the area for the player to begin rebuilding their ship from scratch.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_26_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The default background is a grid of green lines over a black background with a faint image of a pilot's face in the middle.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_26_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The background can be changed, however, to an image taken by the player's webcam."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_27_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm always all ears for what we should do next.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_27_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We hope to eventually do another Summer Achievement Thing -- what level of difficulty do you think makes sense for that?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_27_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>How long does a "fun" achievement take?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_28_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are some great NY-based indies (Wadjet Eye Games springs to mind: http://www.wadjeteyegames.com), so step 1: get to know the folks around you, because they're awesome!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_28_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Second: if you can make the trip to Boston every now and again, DO IT!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_28_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We have a monthly indie meeting (Boston Indies) as well as a more AAA-focused meeting (Boston Post Mortem), the largest of which will draw 50-100 devs at a time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_28_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Then, as trite as it sounds: just make the games you want to make. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_28_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What do you want to do?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_29_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Worst game idea that I love: An open-world, procedurally-generated first-person jetpack shooter that allows the player to explore an entire galaxy of generative content: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4_8WoyEyzzM Best game idea that I love: Girl on robot love action.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_30_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Working alone is one of the worst things I've ever done.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_30_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I got into a sort-of crazy infinite feedback loop/echo chamber with Galaxy Rage (http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4_8WoyEyzzM), where I spent two years on a project and made no progress.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_30_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>BUT: Even if you're working by yourself, you can avoid the "working alone" bit by showing your games off to friends, enemies, frienemies, the press, and so forth.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_30_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Let's see some links to your Flash games!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_32_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Connecticut is PERFECT!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_32_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Let me cheat and cut-and-paste from another answer further down: - gt; If you can make the trip to Boston every now and again, DO IT!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_32_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We have a monthly indie meeting (Boston Indies) as well as a more AAA-focused meeting (Boston Post Mortem), the largest of which will draw 50-100 devs at a time. *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_32_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>gt; Just hop in the indie scene and start cranking stuff out?* *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_32_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>gt; Or to try get in with the big, AAA guys learn their techniques, steal their souls, and then strike out into the indie scene?*</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_32_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Either of these is totally viable.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_32_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I know folks who have done both, and are thriving!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_32_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you're looking for a AAA job, you could do a lot worse than to create some small games and show 'em off.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_32_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What would your ideal day as a game developer look like?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_32_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some other third thing?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_33_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>HELLS yeah!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_33_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I want to have either an inter-booth war or a love-in.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_34_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Fair enough.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_34_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I sometimes have to remember to put myself in the game player's chair and think, "what would *I* actually enjoy playing?"</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_34_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm embarrassed to say, but even as an indie, I forget.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_35_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Andy Schatz from Pocketwatch Games does A MOTHERFUGGING TUX like a bawwwwwwws!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_36_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm thinking that we should all go out and get beers on Friday evening.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_36_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What do you think?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_37_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>**I want all the indies and all the AAAs and all the gamers to go out and get beers on Friday evening**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
