        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_41_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Eitan of Firehouse Studios (creators of Bang Nut Bangers) just put the Q out to a bunch of indies he knew. "</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_41_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hey, who wants to band together and form a BIG-ASS booth for PAX?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_41_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We can get a lot more done as a group than individually."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_41_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So: Eitan's the man to know. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_41_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What's your studio?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_42_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I got to 7, then helicopters kicked my arse.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_42_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt; I really need to learn when to drop an idea thats going nowhere lol Amen.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_42_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But you can also shove it at other game developers and say, "What would YOU do with this next?"</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_42_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You get some reeeeeeally crazy ideas.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_42_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For example, I asked Joseph of Lexaloffle what he thought Drunken Robot Pornography sounds like it'd be, and he sent this: http://www.synthscribe.com/media/drp_(1).png</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_43_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Eitan reached out to a bunch of indies who had been in contact with him, so those became the booth.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_44_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The evolution from http://www.kongregate.com/games/rosyPenguin/vision-by-proxy to http://static4.kizi.com/system/files/vision-by-proxy-2nd-ed.swf?1312706054 is interesting!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_44_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Are you guys going to be in Boston this year?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_45_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yanno, I don't think we have a full Twitter list, but I'm @subject2236.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_46_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can answer part of that: iOS has been pretty good for us indies, in that it's easier to simply create a game and launch it on the App Store than it is to get onto XBLA or PSN.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_46_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Between them and Steam, devs have some solid, indie-friendly avenues.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_46_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Are you returning to Boston for the summer?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_47_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I asked Tommy/Edmund about that, and was sad that they weren't going to be there in the flesh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_47_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What do you guys have going on there?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_48_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Nathan's not here at the moment, but I suspect he'd be happy to give Craig a hug for you. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_49_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Well, then!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_49_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'll be at Made in MA and also look forward to being enforced.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_50_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's both true and kinda messy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_51_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I loved Mass Effect 2 (haven't played 1).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_51_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It was $10 on Steam.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_51_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I *had* to pick it up.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_51_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It was like a Starflight for the '00s.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_52_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>NooooooooooOOOOOOOOOooooooooooooOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOO**OOOOOOO**yes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_52_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Actually, I wonder what he's up to these days?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_53_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Spring is in the air, so a nice medium-heft skirt might actually be comfortable.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_54_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd eat all the AAA's first, because I hear that they aren't starving artists.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_54_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Then, I would eat the Penny Arcade people, because I hear they're delicious.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_54_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Then, I would battle borut_p for who gets to eat the actual MEGABOOTH.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_55_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There's a certain something to be said about sitting down with a bunch of folks over drinks and hashing things out.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_55_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You get the craziest ideas tossed around, rapid-fire, and at the end, you feel simultaneously invigorated and exhausted.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_56_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>* gt; So what would YOU do with my helicopter game next?*</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_56_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd do something that made people, who played it, laugh crazily.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_56_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For example, I might make it easier (testing, testing, testing), and add gobs and gobs of different enemies, each one more absurd than the last.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_56_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe they should invectives as you as you jump over them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_56_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe they start looking like internet memes or unfavorable presidents.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_56_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Anything to get people from "yeah, that's neat" to "Haw!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_56_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I have to share this with my friends."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_56_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Twitter: @subject2236</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_57_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I look forward to meeting you in the person-ness!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_57_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt; Who can compete with MEGABOOOOTHHH?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_57_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Can the MEGABOOTH can compete with the MEGABOOTH?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_57_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Who would win?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_58_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That would be you, Chris.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_59_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I think we should create an indie sitcom at the booth.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_60_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I love this story.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_61_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Are you quoting South Park?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_61_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Anyway, I concur with what NoAndy's saying -- Ugly Baby wasn't fun for about 2 years, and it hurt.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_62_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd have to say it's Kelly, then, because she's awesome, and organized the whole thing. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_63_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's my dream come true, yanno?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_63_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can't say it's for everyone, but it's profitable, and even when it's tough, and the deadlines loom, I can say I'm doing exactly what I love doing.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_63_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some quick tips: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_63_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Network with other devs, indie or no.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_63_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The more I talk to people, the more awesome things just seem to fit. "</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_63_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Oh, you're working on XYZ?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_63_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We should compare notes."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_63_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or: "Oh, let's do an Indie MEGABOOTH."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_63_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Get out there and create stuff, and *show it to people*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_63_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Gamers, devs, your mom.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_63_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Get feedback, tough or gentle.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_63_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And iterate on what you do.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_63_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Those are my top 2. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_64_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I love these: - Tribes 1 - Katamari Damacy - Deus Ex - Koronis Rift ALL of those have inspired me.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_64_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for the indie scene, I think it's actually going to become tougher for small developers to make it over the next decade.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_64_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I see this as being a sort-of "Golden Age," and as more and more larger companies start exploring spaces where indies thrive, it'll be tough.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_64_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But we'll make it anyway. ;)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_65_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm partial to those fruit jelly candies -- either the hemicircular ones or the square prism shaped ones that are coated in sugar.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_66_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I like to step back and think about whether the high concept sounds fun.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_66_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For our latest game, Drunken Robot Pornography, we said, "Hey.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_66_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A human with a jetpack and a nuc-ular weapon picking apart a giant, floating robot piece by piece.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_66_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Dodging lasers and missiles."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_66_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It could work.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_67_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I love that game title. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_68_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>AFTER your panel!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_68_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You're on CA time -- you'll be up until 4 AM EST. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_69_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Innnnnnteresting (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_Winds) -- I don't even think I'd heard of it until just now.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_70_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I have to apologize for that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_70_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But: we have spent the last 4 months moving the game over to a new engine, and hope to show it off at PAX East.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_70_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If that goes well, we'll put that up onto Steam and let everyone play with it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_70_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Here's a quick sketch of all the components we have in for the PAX build: http://www.synthscribe.com/media/ugly_baby_defec_pax_east_sketches.jpg Aaaaa! (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_70_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>F=ma) is iOS for now, but if we can do Android in the future.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_70_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>From what I understand, it's a little trickier than iOS (for a few reasons), but I actually don't have much experience there.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_70_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I *did* pick up a Kindle Fire to see if that was worth supporting, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_70_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, Google broke my heart with my Droid 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_70_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I loved it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_70_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It cheated on me.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_72_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I disagree with Jamezila on #2!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_72_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I mean, his description of the massive persistent ubergame is both right and awesome.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_72_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But I also still just plain love playing games.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_72_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I sometimes dissect them, but mostly am able to turn that part off.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_73_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I started back when the TI 99/4A was a thing, coding up little tiny gamelets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_73_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Around '88, I co-wrote a game called Final Frontier, which was the first thing I ever got proper money for.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_73_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I worked for a small company in the early '90s, and founded Worlds Apart Productions (which became Sony Online Entertainment years after I left) in '95.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_73_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In '99, I said, "Hey.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_73_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And then: ramen.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_73_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And living with my father for too long.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_73_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And more ramen.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_73_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some nice moments breaks: - Figure out the Palm Pilot market - Tying The Wonderful End of the World into a 3D haptic device launch - Getting Steam to notice us for the first time - Working with Valve and other indies in the Portal 2 Potato ARG It all started small, and became slightly less small over time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_74_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I stumbled around a lot before I found my footing.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_74_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You know that image of "what success looks like" (http://tinyurl.com/7p4vcgb)?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_74_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't recommend my path -- yecch.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_74_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>My meta-advice to anyone who wants to go indie is pretty straightforward: find a dozen *successful* indies who are creating games the way you want to create them, and are living the lifestyle you want to live.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_74_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Then, ask them the question of how they'd do it if they were starting out now.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_74_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>My advice is always: a) create many little things b) network.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_74_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By doing that, a picture will begin to form.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_75_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>#One: Those are the three games we're showing off at PAX East.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_75_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>F=ma (the iOS version of Aaaaa!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_75_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>and the others are new.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_75_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>$Two: They all seem to differ.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_75_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The original Aaaaa!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_75_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>went like this: Dec '08 was the spark that started it all; Jan '09 was the series of prototypes; Aug '09 was the beta; and Sep '09 was the launch.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_75_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ugly Baby went like this: Sep '09 was the prototype; (insert a year of me fumbling around); Apr '11 was the pre-release launch on Steam; (insert most of a year of me fumbling around again); Mar '12 started the move to the Unity Prototype; aaaaaaaand we're here. !</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_75_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Three: We're now totally a Unity shop, though we used to use a nice (but simpler) engine called 3D Gamestudio.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_75_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Python's my personal favorite language -- if I could use that more for game logic, I would.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_75_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But we use it for many of our tools.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_75_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>~Four: Thank you. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_76_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some of the other folks might be able to give you a better answer, but in Unity, we just use PhysX (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PhysX), and I know others use Box2D (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box2D).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_76_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've never written anything more complex than a box/sphere based collision system, but I salute your interest in digging deeper -- a game dev should know the low-level stuff, imo.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_78_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I absolutely see that connection.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_79_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Screenshots in no particular order.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_79_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But generally, in chronological order.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_80_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The playable pre-release is, but it's not a finished game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_81_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt; Dejobaan could have managed this better.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_81_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yes; we could have, and I apologize for that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_81_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you read through these blog posts, you'll see what we've been up to: http://www.subject2236.com/category/uglybaby It's been a tougher dev cycle than I'd hoped, but that's some of the concrete stuff we've been doing to push development forward.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_82_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yeah; and I feel silly for bungling it -- it's taken longer than I expected.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_82_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Here's what we're doing to complete the game: http://www.subject2236.com/category/uglybaby</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_83_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's still in development; we'll keep working until it's fun.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_84_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'd be right.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_84_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And your friend is magical.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_85_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We actually did this to some extent in our 2004 title, Inago Rage -- DRP's sort-of a spiritual successor to that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_85_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In DRP, the bullet hell factor seems to work best when we do a bunch of big, slowly-moving, variously-oriented columns in space.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_85_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your brain tends to then view that as a big, shifting 3D maze.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_86_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I always love hearing about the development process.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_86_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What's the one big, bad, awesome feature you had to drop to get this game out the door -- and will it make an appearance in Mega Sixty Second Shooter Turbo?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm sitting here on my couch, and I just received a text from LJ telling me that we got hundreds of requests for testing so far.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thank you all. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some info about the game: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The original game was all about boss battles.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Destroy Titans, piece-by-piece while flying around on a jetpack.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Neat concept, I think.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The prototype was nice -- your opponent had different weapons, and could carve you up with lasers or do a neat 3D bullet-hell type thing that you had to weave through in spaaace.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>BUT the action was kinda "meh."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You could defeat the Titan by circle-strafing.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So, we took some notes from our 2004 title, Inago Rage (here's an ANCIENT trailer: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HCfHTlsbplk).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We added powerups to triple and sextuple your bullet output, little drone robots, shields, accelerators, bouncers, and more stuff.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This Steam alpha is our first real public test of things.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Valve just opened up a forum for this (http://forums.steampowered.com/forums/forumdisplay.php?s=0b5200f242c2da4abba2b85336de9ee9 amp;f=1533 -- thanks Burton!),</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>and we'll be sending out keys... Sunday, probably?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Then: the tough love.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_88_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Loooooooooove.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_89_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Notes: * This is a vid FirstPersonStranger made of a bunch of player-created Titans. *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_89_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's for Drunken Robot Pornography. *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_89_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We just posted a quickie trailer here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mQzOyuiV_bg * Steam forums here: http://forums.steampowered.com/forums/forumdisplay.php?f=1533 * Website here: www.subject2236.com/drunken</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_90_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I said, "Goddamnit, why isn't our fan club working!?"</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_90_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>and then ljaitley re-jiggered it all and made it good.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_90_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Either that, or it got shunted to your spam folder. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_91_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yeah, for free!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_91_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Besides, you live like 156 hours north of us.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_92_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>No OS X yet.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_92_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We're hoping to do it, since Unity makes it easy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_92_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But we need to get ElliotDejobaan a beefy Mac first.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_92_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or any Mac.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_93_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You know, we created this game, but we've never actually gotten a copy of it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_94_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We're a small indie studio with a few titles on Steam.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_94_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We've worked with a number of folks on our projects over the years, and the best formula (for us!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_94_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>seems to be like this: * Do something small and awesome. *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_94_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finish it so you can show it off and talk about it. *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_94_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Find like-minded folks and get to know them over the course of months (or years) by talking about what you do. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_94_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's possible to do this online, but I really like local game dev events.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_94_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You get to know people well over beer or coffee.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_94_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Eventually, we and the right people just seem to gravitate towards either other.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_94_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>From there, broaching the topic of collaboration is occasionally like asking someone out on a date -- it's awkward, at first, pleasantly surprising that the other person wants to collaborate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_95_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I actually think you're doing a lot right, and that app discovery is simply *really difficult for small developers on the App Store in 2013*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_95_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We've released an iOS title that was: * In New and Noteworthy * Given a big-ass honking feature * Game of the Week in multiple countries * Solidly 5-star rated by users * Critically praised (Metacritic listed it as [#10 of the top 25](http://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-ios-games-of-2012) best iOS games of the year) ...and yet, **the PC version has easily outsold it by a factor of 10**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_95_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's not too surprising for us to run into PC gamers who have heard of the title, but rarely an iOS gamer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_95_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We haven't solved this problem, so I can't say for certain what'll work, but some food for thought: * Check out the landing pages for successful iOS titles and see if you can glean something from them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_95_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For example, many have text on the screenshots that sell the game. *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_95_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Have you hit as many press outlets as you can? (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_95_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>E.g., TouchArcade, 148Apps, Slide to Play, etc.) *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_95_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I actually might recommend against lowering the price.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_95_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We raised the price of our game, and are generating more revenue.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_95_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Anyway, I like the art style, and hope you guys do well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_95_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I see that you also have a Greenlight submission up; best of luck on both!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_96_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Two great ways are meetup.com and the IGDA.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_96_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The former may list a number of informal game dev meetings in the area (I believe our own Boston Indies meetings must have started that way), an the latter are more formalized.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_96_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You could also do what Andy Moore of Radial Games did, and just start one up.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_96_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He lived in Victoria, BC, Canadia, and just started posting about a pub meetup he wanted to have.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_96_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And he kept going.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_96_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Until one person showed up; then two; and ten... By the time he was done, the group was 200 strong!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_97_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But even without that, the PC version outsold the iOS version by an order of magnitude -- and I think the iOS version is sexier.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_98_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's 5 groups of 5.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_98_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I sat down next to one of my friends who was helping out with the PR side of things, and he literally would not let me leave until I named it that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_99_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That makes sense!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_99_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I only have anecdotal evidence from a handful of indie developers, but I personally think indies price too low.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It may be worth having a lawyer peek at whatever you draft (if you're just starting out, you might be able to find one willing to do it pro bono).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Either way, [Nolo's](http://www.nolo.com/) not a bad resource for this kind of form.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But generally, we'll use a format like this:  gt; Independent Contractor Agreement for Artist  gt;  gt; This agreement is made between (us here) ("Client") and (contractor here) ("Contractor").</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt;  gt; 1: Services to be Performed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt;  gt; Contractor agrees to perform the following work for Client:  gt;  gt; Create ____ based on discussion with Client.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt;  gt; Deliver to Client all ____ in electronic format on or before ____.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt;  gt; 2: Consideration.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt;  gt; In consideration for the services to be performed by Contractor:  gt;  gt; Client agrees to pay Contractor a flat fee of ____.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Contractor shall be paid in full upon completion of Contractor's services and receipt of invoice.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt;  gt; (etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There's a bunch of boilerplate you may want to pick and choose from.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For example, do you want a bit about confidentiality?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Where do you want disputes to be resolved?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a resource, here's an off-the-shelf generic independent contractor (creative) agreement: http://www.nolo.com/products/independent-contractor-agreement-for-creative-contractor-for-firm-pr227.html.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_100_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, assuming you're both in the US, you'll want to issue them a W-9 (http://turbotax.intuit.com/tax-tools/tax-tips/IRS-Tax-Forms/What-is-IRS-Form-W-9-/INF20088.html) so that you can later issue them a 1099-MISC, because the IRS loves making us all fill out a bunch of forms.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_101_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We Bostonites try to help our fellow devs out when they come into town, but it sounds like we just missed you completely.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_101_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There's this whole built-in community around here (Boston Indies and Boston Post Mortem), with (literally) hundreds of people interested or directly involved in indie gaming.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_101_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Folks volunteer to help each other get food or drink, or to take over a booth for a bit -- or even to just say, "Yanno, it's okay if you abandon your post take a rest.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_101_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We'll make sure nobody steals your shit."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_101_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you're in town, showing at this year's PAX (or if anyone reading this is), reach out to the community.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_101_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We're all handsome, beautiful, and sexy people.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_101_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, we smell nice.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_102_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also got updates on the Facebook page: www.facebook.com/subject2236 I don't tweet that much, but also @subject2236.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_102_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And I think we have a Pinterest page, but it's mostly for tracking our macram patterns.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_102_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, for your amusent, here's our work-in-progress music video for the title screen: https://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_embedded amp;v=eR73chGfiXQ</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_103_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yup: we just released a new update this past weekend (Jan 25th); if you haven't done so already, check it out.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_103_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The new version should automatically update if you own (and have installed) the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_103_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Here's the Steam forum page with what's new: http://forums.steampowered.com/forums/showthread.php?t=3065186 Here's a video of the previous update that we posted last month: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NGtuBYSzx9c And an aesthetics vid we posted early December: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1lDLpLDNHH8 amp;list=UUq9oPCxcXnzTVl1s4c6iGkA Let us know if you like what you see.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_104_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>@Moncole: Yeah.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_104_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We actually HAD an AaaaaAAaaaAAAaaAAAAaAAAAA!!!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_104_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>demo out, but I did a shitty job of it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_104_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>People were playing it and saying, "I picked the full game up *despite* the demo -- boy, am I glad I did."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_104_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So, I killed the demo.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_104_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Because it sucked.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_104_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Someday, if there's enough interest, we'll do one.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_104_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But it'd have to be a less bad one.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_105_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Much of the bullet hell comes from what are (essentially) tall, moving cylinders.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_105_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So, ideally, intersections with the level architecture help the eye gauge distance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_105_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But give it a go and let us know what you think.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_106_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ahahahahaha!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We (Dejobaan) have been reasonably successful (we are on our 17th title, and will hopefully be in business for years to come), and while I'll often work 60 hour weeks, a good work/life balance always helps.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Here's why I think so: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Taking time away helps me solve problems in unusual ways.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When I'm working, my brain tends to focus narrowly on a problem.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So, I'll tend to explore something deeply but ignore anything that's not obvious. ("</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Damnit, this level is taking too long to load.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I must optimize the loading functions to shave off 1.1 seconds.")</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The time I spend walking, showering, or taking a crap (not all at once, usually) is time my brain just wanders, and can make really neat connections. ("</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Oh, holy crap.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Instead of spending five hours getting a 0.5% decrease in loading time, what if I just do something to entertain the player during load?")</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It allows me to be more creative in my design for the same reason.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When I'm not in the "MUST BE PRODUCTIVE AT ALL COSTS" mode, I'll start to think about how to give our games more character.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For example, in one of our games, I decided to stick elevator music into the level select screen; in another, I drafted a(n admittedly amateurish) rap song for the title.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>These were tiny things, but people loved them, and the press talked about both.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Related to #1, limiting my hours forces me to solve problems in ways other than "Gee, I'll just toss more of my time at it."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For example, I'll spend 10 hours talking to people about helping me on level design rather than committing myself to spending 8 hours a week for 8 weeks designing all the levels, myself.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And related to /that/, the more time I spend socializing, the more people I randomly meet - and some of those help me make better games.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, some years ago, I decided to suck up my pride and try to learn salsa dancing.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Through that, I ended up meeting the dude who's now my biz dev guy (I would never have expected that).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I also met my wife though that, and aside from that being great in its own right, she works in a creative industry, and consults for us. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>She gives us good rates.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_21</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Similarly, taking time to get to know other game devs socially has resulted in project collaborations.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_22</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Suddenly, there's this network of people who want to work together on all these amazing projects.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_107_23</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So, I'll agree with those folks posting here: if you're spending 90h/week working, you are probably missing out on a lot of awesome stuff!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_108_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There will be another Indie Megabooth this year.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_108_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We (Dejobaan!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_108_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>will be showing off Drunken Robot Pornography, Monster Loves You! (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_108_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>with Canadian indie Radial Games), and Drop That Beat Like an Ugly Baby.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_108_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for tips: talk to all the indie devs there.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_108_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The folks working the booths are the ones actually doing the coding, art, design, and so forth.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_108_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A potential positive to balance out the fact that our games are smaller and less glamorous than AAA titles. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_109_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So, this is a game we've been working on for about three years.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_109_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We first launched a playable pre-release during the Portal 2 ARG.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_109_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You remember that?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_109_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That was, like, in 2011.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_109_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For the year after that, we were just spinning our wheels and sucking great bags of crappy game development.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_109_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We then did a Unity prototype, and brought Zapdot around to help us with it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_109_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's Michael Carriere and Dave Evans (on loan from Hybrid Mind Studios).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_109_7</DOCNO>
