        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_105</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>============================================================= **December 19th, 2012** Update Name: Alex Is Nude Ladies and gents, may I present you with the first playable Steam pre-release build in about 50 billion years.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_106</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Details: - Lots of research on Procedural Content Generation (PCG). -</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_107</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We re-wrote the game from the ground up in Unity.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_108</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's now all in Unity + Python, making it moddable and wonderful. -</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_109</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There's a new music analysis engine called BeatBox, which Andy Eiche created.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_110</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We're just beginning to make use of this. -</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_111</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The guys from fellow Boston indie studios Zapdot (Michael Carriere) and Hybrid Mind Studios (Dave Evans) are working with us full time now.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_112</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Michael's focused on Unity, and Dave and I are focused on the PCG side of things. -</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_113</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In the past year and a half, we've tested dozens of mechanics.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_114</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What you're seeing is the very first Unity build we're releasing to the wild.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_115</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Let us know what you think.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_116</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>NOTE: We're trying a few new things out in this build.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_117</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some will be awesome; some, we'll want to change.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_118</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Let us know what you like and feel we could improve.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_119</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>============================================================= So, that's what we have.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_120</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you picked up the game during the Portal 2 ARG, give the game a go now, and tell me what you think.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_121</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can re-snag it at http://store.steampowered.com/app/15540.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_122</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We're going to keep building on it and polishing until we're utterly proud of it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_116_123</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thank you for reading.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_117_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thanks, DC. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_118_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I just received the following IM:  gt; **04/12 - 03:46PM Michael Carriere:** http://www.reddit.com/r/gamedev/comments/1c7oe9/im_a_composer_looking_for_a_game_to_score_and_i/  gt;  gt; **04/12 - 03:47PM Michael Carriere:** do itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo it**do itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo itdo it**  gt;  gt; **04/12 - 03:48PM Ichiro:** 48 pieces???</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_118_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt;  gt; **04/12 - 03:48PM Michael Carriere:** that is amazing  gt;  gt; **04/12 - 03:48PM Michael Carriere:** "Drop that Beat Like an Ugly Baby comes with a soundtrack made from a 48 piece orchestra"  gt;  gt; **04/12 - 03:49PM Ichiro:** Okay, I'll check it out.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_118_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Michael wants me to reply to this.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_118_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So: we're Dejobaan Games, best known for our IGF finalist, AaaaaAAaaaAAAaaAAAAaAAAAA!!! --</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_118_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A Reckless Disregard for Gravity, our work on Valve's Portal 2 Potato ARG, and so forth.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_118_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We just launched Monster Loves You!,</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_118_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>our 5th Steam title (http://store.steampowered.com/search/?snr=1_7_7_230_12 amp;term=subject2236), and have two games up on Steam's Early Access, if you are familiar with that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_118_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We're creating a game around music (Drop That Beat Like an Ugly Baby: http://store.steampowered.com/video/15540/2028493), and would love to chat. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_120_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We launched it as a playable pre-release -- what you had was the first public version.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_120_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And now, what you have looks completely different, and will continue to improve (hopefully!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_120_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>until it's at v1.0. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_121_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You're both right!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_121_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We haven't focused on showing this in the alpha trailer that's up there, but what we want is a core experience that includes an original soundtrack we compose (one that tells the game's narrative), but then opens up to allow players to play their own music.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_122_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is most delightful to me.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_122_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thank you for saying so.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_123_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thank you so much. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_123_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's really nice to hear that, as we try to put a lot of our own character into our games.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_123_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Creating them is a joy, and (hopefully) that'll shine through when folks play 'em!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_124_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We think, "Hey, we can name the game whatever we want.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_124_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Let's have fun with it."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_124_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We come up with a pile of them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_124_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We figure out which of them are remarkable (i.e. if I wrote a journalist about our game, s/he would talk about it).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_124_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We figure out which of *those* are descriptive.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_124_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I make the final judgement call, because committee can be bad. * **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_124_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>AaaaaAAaaaAAAaaAAAAaAAAAA!!! --</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_124_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A Reckless Disregard for Gravity** (A game about BASE jumping.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_124_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It was long enough that it broke Steam.) * **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_124_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Drop That Beat Like an Ugly Baby** (A game about music and how the world is messy and poops itself a lot) * **Drunken Robot Pornography** (A game about fighting a dozen robots including your former bartender) Not everyone likes our names (not everyone has to).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_124_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But they're distinctive, and show that we don't take ourselves too seriously.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_125_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>@zapdot: You gave me that footage. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_126_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I still stand by that comment. ;)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_126_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By the same token, when people turn their ideas into games, however simple or small: that's wonderful, and it makes me happy and hopeful.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_127_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Played this at GDC.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_128_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I used to twiddle pixels back in the day.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_128_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>My colleagues all use Unity, but I've fallen behind -- I'm not sure if this has practical utility, but I'm glad you're doing it. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_129_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is most delightful -- thank you for the kind words!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_130_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Trevor, get back into your monkey cave!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_131_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As backstory (WTH is this?),</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_131_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>it's our upcoming Steam Early Access title: http://www.subject2236.com/drunken/ * Here's a trailer: http://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_embedded amp;v=mQzOyuiV_bg * A nice Classic Game Room preview: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ONPgot7jqxU * The music video that is the DRP title menu rap: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eR73chGfiXQ * Time lapse video of us creating a Titan: http://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_embedded amp;v=HkpZOcf0rog</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_132_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We recently published our first visual novel ("Monster Loves You!")</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_132_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's our 17th title as a studio, and our 6th Steam title, and has been our single best launch-week seller yet.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_132_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So: I think there's money to be made in the genre if you do it right.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_132_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I were in your position, and I wanted to attract a dev team, I would do this: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_132_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Get to know as many developers as possible.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_132_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Network like crazy and make friends.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_132_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This may take a while.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_132_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Mock up a compelling 15m experience and be able to run people through it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_132_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We did this for MLY, and since it was narrative-based, we were able to just sit people down at a table and have them pretend to play the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_132_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It conveyed things perfectly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_132_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Research why a visual novel will sell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_132_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Talk to authors of other novels; search for articles on costs and profits.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_132_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sit your new game dev friends down, run them through your simulated game, and afterwards, explain why your game will earn a profit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_132_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are many ways you can pull a team together, but that's worked for me in the past.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_133_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I think there will be.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_133_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Matt is one of those guys who won't give up.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_133_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He's awesome and tenacious.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_134_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's my home town. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I run a [studio (link here)](http://www.subject2236.com) that's been around for a number of years, with several profitable Steam titles, and my second iOS game on the way.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've worked in the industry on and off since around 1993, so with that perspective, here's what I might do in your place: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Spend $1500 going to PAX Prime and talking to every independent developer you can.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Take some of them out to coffee, and pick their brains.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are several there who started out as you are, and work with that kind of budget.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They can give you tips on what they've done right and wrong, and how the market's been shifting.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Similarly, pick out which industry conferences you want to go to, and budget for those.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've met developers at events such as GDC, and later partnered with them to develop our stuff.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Meeting with publishers and distributors here is also useful.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Go through Gamasutra's backlog for the past 10 years, pick out every article that looks pertinent to what you're doing, and read it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There's some gems there.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you're willing: be okay with the prospect of building something tiny first.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've been doing this for a while, and I still underestimate the amount of time it takes to create a game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And I still fuck up all the time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Starting small allows you to fail gracefully and learn from it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thoughts on what you're asking, specifically:  gt; What are some real world expected salaries for indie game devs?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Check out the Gamasutra Salary Survey (http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/130444/game_development_salary_survey_2003.php) for starters, though that's not set in stone.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt; what kind of business related expenses should I consider? *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Conferences/conventions (travel, booth space, etc.). *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Office space (I like working under the same roof as my team, though people differ -- co-working spaces are relatively low-risk). *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Legal fees.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_21</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You might want a lawyer to look over a distribution agreement or draft a work-for-hire, for instance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_22</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt; What are some other things I should take into consideration?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_23</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Check your response to AD1337's post:  gt; "The only thing childish here is your negative response..." Regardless of whether s/he's objectively right or wrong, or if feedback is useful to you or not, focusing on the positives will get other game devs to want to help you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_24</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe you think AD1337's being childish, but why not just ignore the parts you don't like?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_25</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you do end up creating a successful game, people from the Internet are going to shit all over you much worse.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_26</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And in some instances, they're going to mean well, and because we're speaking through a text medium, you're going to interpret it a certain way.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_27</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Bypass that instinct, take the good bits, and ignore the bad.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_135_28</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>More often than not, you'll be closer to the poster's intent.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_136_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Naw, Andy is the Radial Games half of our latest. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_137_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thanks for the kind words. :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_137_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We picked Drunken Robot Pornography as the name because we like to have fun with our titles.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_137_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The "Drunken Robot" part has to do with the antagonist, who's a former robot bartender. "</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_137_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Pornography" to mean both that there's a sort of lascivious interest in the robots (see also "furniture porn") and that there are 12 big bosses.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_137_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, I wanted to see whether Valve would say "yes." :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_138_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Why do you have the owl from Clash of the Titans on your desk?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_139_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Python's my personal favorite language for game development.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_139_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We use it a great deal for PCG.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_139_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm hesitant to make the leap to 3.x, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_139_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm still running 2.6/2.7.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_140_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We'll look into FLAC once we get gameplay down pat -- we've specifically been ignoring it in favor of making the game more fun.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_140_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But that doesn't mean we hate FLAC.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_141_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's tough to say, since we can't do an A/B test (Aaaaa/Bbbbb test?),</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_141_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>but I think the unusual name's turned out well for us over the years.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_141_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>People seem to remember that it's got a bunch of A's, so when (for example), they see it on Steam, they'll remember it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_141_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Plus, it got the press interested when we first announced it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_141_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Bonus story: When we launched on Steam, we broke Steam because of the name.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_141_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They eventually fixed that, and (I'm told) instituted the "Aaaaa!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_141_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>test" to make sure text fields can handle long titles.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_142_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Never wear a red shirt and stand by the rail.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_142_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If only these characters would listen!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_143_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For [Monster Loves You!](http://www.subject2236.com/monster/), we developed a language called Boa.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_143_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've worked with various graphical methods and markup languages over the years, and Boa's my all-around favorite.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_143_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Here's a snippet that may illustrate how it works: Hey, this is a dialog. -</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_143_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>gt; This is choice #1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_143_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is a response to choice #1. -</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_143_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>gt; This is choice #2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_143_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is a response to choice #2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_143_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But wait, there's more! -</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_723_143_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>gt; [Variable1==2] Choice #3 is only visible if Variable1 is 2.</TEXT>
